3	veteran_status	veteran	0	This bill replaces the federal tax system with a national sales tax and affects all taxpayers identically; veterans are not treated differently and their status is irrelevant.	1.00	{"0": 3}
3	disability_status	has_disability	0	This is a broad tax overhaul replacing income/payroll taxes with a national sales tax; it applies uniformly regardless of disability status. The bill does not treat people with disabilities differently from others.	0.67	{"0": 2, "1": 1}
3	student_status	student	1	The bill defines 'education and training' (including postsecondary tuition and job-related training) as intermediate services not subject to the new national sales tax, so students' tuition and training costs are affected by this specific carve-out. This is a first-order effect tied to their student status, though students are not the bill's explicit primary subject.	0.67	{"1": 2, "2": 1}
3	student_loan_status	has_student_loans	0	The bill replaces the income tax system with a national sales tax and does not address student loans, their repayment, interest, or forgiveness; borrowers are not treated differently based on holding student loans.	1.00	{"0": 3}
3	caregiver_status	parent_of_minor	1	This broad tax overhaul provides a monthly family consumption allowance whose amount scales with qualified family size, and minor children (lineal descendants, adopted children, and children under guardianship sharing a residence) are counted as family members. Thus having a minor child directly increases the rebate a household receives, a first-order effect tied to the trait.	0.67	{"1": 2, "2": 1}
3	caregiver_status	caregiver_of_adult	1	A dependent adult relative (e.g., a lineal ancestor) sharing a common residence would be counted in the qualified family for rebate purposes, so caring for such an adult in the household affects the family consumption allowance. However, the caregiving relationship itself is not the explicit trigger—household residence and family relationship are—making the effect first-order but indirect.	0.67	{"0": 1, "1": 2}
3	housing_status	homeowner	1	The national sales tax applies to purchases of new homes while excluding used property, so buying newly built housing would incur the 23% tax; existing homeowners' ongoing occupancy is untaxed, making the effect a first-order consequence tied to home purchases.	1.00	{"1": 3}
3	housing_status	renter	2	The bill explicitly defines taxable property to include leaseholds and rents, so residential rent would be directly subject to the national sales tax, an immediate firsthand effect on renters.	1.00	{"2": 3}
3	housing_status	other	1	Those living with family, unhoused, or in institutional settings generally would not pay a housing-consumption tax on rent or new-home purchases, so the housing-related tax treatment differs for this group as a first-order effect.	0.67	{"0": 1, "1": 2}
3	citizenship_status	citizen	2	The bill replaces income/payroll taxes with a national sales tax paid by all consumers, and the Family Consumption Allowance rebate explicitly requires listed members to be lawful residents with a bona fide SSN—criteria citizens satisfy. Citizenship status is an explicit condition determining rebate eligibility, making the effect direct and trait-dependent.	1.00	{"2": 3}
3	citizenship_status	permanent_resident	2	Permanent residents are 'lawful residents of the United States' with SSNs, so they are directly subject to the sales tax and eligible for the family consumption rebate under the bill's explicit residency certification requirements.	1.00	{"2": 3}
3	citizenship_status	other_status	2	The rebate registration requires certifying all counted family members are lawful residents with bona fide SSNs, so undocumented persons and some other-status individuals are excluded from the rebate while still paying the sales tax—an explicit, trait-dependent distinction.	1.00	{"2": 3}
3	marital_status	single	1	The bill's family consumption allowance rebate is available to all filers, but the amount is boosted only for families that include a married couple via the 'annual marriage penalty elimination amount.' Single (unmarried) filers receive the baseline rebate without that add-on, a differential tied to marital status.	1.00	{"1": 3}
3	marital_status	married	2	Married couples are an explicit subject: Section 303 grants an 'annual marriage penalty elimination amount' that increases the monthly poverty-level rebate specifically for families including a married couple, and spouse status directly shapes qualified-family composition and registration.	1.00	{"2": 3}
3	marital_status	divorced	2	Section 302(c)(2) contains an explicit rule for children of divorced or separated parents, assigning the child to the custodial parent's qualified family for rebate purposes, directly affecting divorced individuals' rebate calculations.	0.67	{"1": 1, "2": 2}
3	marital_status	widowed	0	The bill contains no provision specific to widowhood; a widowed person is treated like any other single-member household.	0.67	{"0": 2, "1": 1}
3	age	under_18	0	Minors are counted only as members of a qualified family for the consumption-allowance rebate; the tax overhaul does not affect them distinctly based on being under 18.	1.00	{"0": 3}
3	age	age_18_25	0	As workers and consumers they are affected by the income/payroll tax repeal and sales tax, but the effect does not differ specifically because of this age.	1.00	{"0": 3}
3	age	age_26_49	0	Affected as taxpayers and consumers like all adults, with no effect that varies distinctly by this age bracket.	1.00	{"0": 3}
3	age	age_50_64	0	Affected as workers/consumers under the tax overhaul, but the bill produces no age-specific effect for this pre-retirement bracket.	1.00	{"0": 3}
3	age	age_65_plus	1	The bill includes an explicit sales-tax-inclusive Social Security benefits indexation (Sec. 303) and shifts Social Security/Medicare from payroll-tax to general-revenue funding, and a consumption tax bears differently on retirees spending down savings, creating an age-linked first-order effect.	1.00	{"1": 3}
3	income	under_30k	2	The bill repeals income and payroll taxes and imposes a national sales tax plus a family consumption allowance (rebate) tied to the poverty level, directly and firsthand affecting low-income households' overall tax burden. The rebate mechanism is especially consequential at this income level, where consumption is a large share of income.	1.00	{"2": 3}
3	income	income_30k_60k	2	Households in this bracket are directly subject to the new sales tax and eligible for the poverty-level rebate, with elimination of payroll and income taxes altering their firsthand tax situation. The net effect differs from other brackets based on consumption-to-income ratios.	1.00	{"2": 3}
3	income	income_60k_120k	2	This group is an explicit subject of the bill, directly facing the shift from income/payroll taxation to consumption taxation with the fixed rebate. The change in tax liability is immediate and its magnitude varies by income level.	1.00	{"2": 3}
3	income	income_120k_250k	2	Higher-income households are directly affected by repeal of the income tax and the new sales tax, with the flat rebate representing a smaller share of their consumption. The firsthand tax burden shift differs distinctly at this bracket.	1.00	{"2": 3}
3	income	income_250k_plus	2	The bill directly repeals income, estate, and gift taxes—provisions especially salient at the highest incomes—and substitutes a consumption tax, immediately restructuring this group's tax obligations. The effect differs markedly from lower brackets given estate tax repeal and consumption patterns.	1.00	{"2": 3}
3	occupation	education	1	The bill specifically carves out education and training tuition, treating it as an untaxed business-type input rather than taxed final consumption, distinguishing the education sector's treatment from other services.	0.67	{"0": 1, "1": 2}
