5	119	hr	38	Constitutional Concealed Carry Reciprocity Act of 2025	floor	Crime and Law Enforcement	2025-01-03	https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/house-bill/38	Placed on the Union Calendar, Calendar No. 289.	2025-10-03	2026-02-04 05:06:18+00	2026-07-16 05:34:16.549444+00	4be17fc6b83035d5009b5c20af48fe941d0da541c0573202d5ee163f607ec7d8	Reported in House	https://www.congress.gov/119/bills/hr38/BILLS-119hr38rh.htm	complete	claude-opus-4-8	1	1	2026-07-16 05:35:21.508356+00	4be17fc6b83035d5009b5c20af48fe941d0da541c0573202d5ee163f607ec7d8	Allows people with a valid concealed-carry permit from one state to carry a concealed handgun in most other states.	This bill, called the Constitutional Concealed Carry Reciprocity Act of 2025, changes federal law (title 18 of the United States Code) so that a person who is legally allowed to carry a concealed handgun in their home state can also carry it in other states. This applies as long as the person is not banned from having firearms under federal law and carries both a photo ID and a valid concealed-carry license or permit.\n\nThe rule covers any state that either lets its own residents apply for a concealed-carry permit or does not ban residents from carrying concealed firearms. It does not override the right of private property owners to ban guns on their property, and it does not override state or local rules that restrict guns on government property, buildings, or bases. It also lets permit holders carry concealed handguns in certain federal public lands, such as national parks, wildlife refuges, and Forest Service land.\n\nThe bill adds legal protections for people who carry under these rules. Police cannot arrest someone just for carrying unless there is probable cause of a violation, and in court the government must prove beyond a reasonable doubt that the person did not follow the law. People who win such cases, or who sue because their rights under this section were denied, can be awarded damages and attorney's fees.\n\nThe changes would take effect 90 days after the bill becomes law. Those directly affected include people who hold concealed-carry permits and travel between states, state and local governments and law enforcement who must apply the new standard, and courts that handle related cases.	2026-07-16 05:33:45.57419+00	2026-07-16 05:35:10.78978+00
2	119	hr	22	SAVE Act	passed_house	Government Operations and Politics	2025-01-03	https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/house-bill/22	Received in the Senate.	2025-04-10	2026-07-11 03:23:18+00	2026-07-16 05:34:01.41763+00	a3beb76d08e3f09aa020d84075bbb18da7cdc1cfe05ce33fb9c722f5a39b4587	Engrossed in House	https://www.congress.gov/119/bills/hr22/BILLS-119hr22eh.htm	complete	claude-opus-4-8	1	1	2026-07-16 05:36:18.938028+00	a3beb76d08e3f09aa020d84075bbb18da7cdc1cfe05ce33fb9c722f5a39b4587	Requires people to show documentary proof of U.S. citizenship when registering to vote in federal elections and directs states to remove noncitizens from voter rolls.	This bill changes the National Voter Registration Act of 1993 to require that anyone registering to vote in federal elections show a document proving they are a U.S. citizen. Accepted documents include a REAL ID-compliant identification card showing citizenship, a valid U.S. passport, certain military IDs, or a government photo ID paired with items such as a certified birth certificate, a naturalization certificate, or a Consular Report of Birth Abroad. States could not accept or process a registration application unless this proof is provided.\n\nThe bill sets rules for how proof is presented under each registration method, including at motor vehicle offices, through the national mail-in form, and at voter registration agencies. For people who cannot supply a listed document, states must create a process allowing them to sign a sworn statement and submit other evidence, which an election official then reviews. States must also take ongoing steps to confirm only citizens are registered, using databases such as the Department of Homeland Security's Systematic Alien Verification for Entitlements (SAVE) system and Social Security records, and must remove noncitizens from voter rolls when they receive verified information.\n\nThe measure adds criminal penalties for election officials who register applicants without proof of citizenship and for executive branch employees who help noncitizens register or vote. It also allows private lawsuits over violations. The Department of Homeland Security must notify state election officials when someone becomes a naturalized citizen. The Election Assistance Commission must issue guidance to states, and the bill states that eligible voters may still cast provisional ballots.\n\nThose directly affected include people registering or re-registering to vote in federal elections, state and local election officials who process registrations, state motor vehicle and voter registration agencies, and federal agencies asked to verify citizenship. People without easy access to citizenship documents would need to use the alternative process the states must set up.	2026-07-16 05:33:45.508218+00	2026-07-16 05:35:10.78978+00
8	119	s	1582	GENIUS Act	enacted	Finance and Financial Sector	2025-05-01	https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/senate-bill/1582	Became Public Law No: 119-27.	2025-07-18	2026-03-12 15:11:43+00	2026-07-16 05:34:48.101643+00	0da64b016b86b2d2081a2a84ed31c237334cfd2d4bd87478b5f8e7f5d57f3344	Public Law	https://www.congress.gov/119/plaws/publ27/PLAW-119publ27.htm	complete	claude-opus-4-8	1	1	2026-07-16 05:35:44.38831+00	0da64b016b86b2d2081a2a84ed31c237334cfd2d4bd87478b5f8e7f5d57f3344	Creates federal and state rules for companies that issue payment stablecoins, requiring full reserves, regular disclosures, and consumer protections.	This law, called the Guiding and Establishing National Innovation for U.S. Stablecoins Act (GENIUS Act), sets up rules for a type of digital money called a payment stablecoin. A stablecoin is a digital asset designed to keep a steady value, usually tied to the U.S. dollar. Under the law, only approved companies\\called permitted payment stablecoin issuers\\can issue these coins in the United States.\n\nCompanies that issue stablecoins must back every coin fully with safe assets like cash, bank deposits, or short-term Treasury bills. They must publish monthly reports on their reserves, have those reports checked by an outside accounting firm, and clearly explain their rules and fees for redeeming coins. Issuers cannot pay interest to coin holders, cannot use misleading names suggesting the coins are backed by the U.S. government, and must follow anti-money laundering and sanctions laws. Larger issuers can be regulated at the federal level, while smaller ones (under $10 billion in coins) may be overseen by states if their rules are judged similar to the federal ones.\n\nThe law also sets rules for coins issued by foreign companies, requiring them to meet comparable standards and comply with U.S. legal orders before their coins can be sold here. It spells out how customer coins are protected if an issuer goes bankrupt, giving coin holders priority claims. It also clarifies that these stablecoins are not treated as securities or commodities under existing financial laws.\n\nThose directly affected include companies that issue or handle digital assets, banks and credit unions that offer related services, federal regulators such as the Treasury Department and the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, state regulators, and people who buy or hold stablecoins. Most rules take effect within about 18 months after enactment.	2026-07-16 05:33:45.629641+00	2026-07-16 05:35:10.78978+00
9	119	s	331	HALT Fentanyl Act	enacted	Crime and Law Enforcement	2025-01-30	https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/senate-bill/331	Became Public Law No: 119-26.	2025-07-16	2026-03-12 15:04:04+00	2026-07-16 05:34:42.932716+00	3409d4f42bf26cd1ce6849217614b6c9216375c40d670890c0b10e1d89d24b3d	Public Law	https://www.congress.gov/119/plaws/publ26/PLAW-119publ26.htm	complete	claude-opus-4-8	1	1	2026-07-16 05:35:52.506775+00	3409d4f42bf26cd1ce6849217614b6c9216375c40d670890c0b10e1d89d24b3d	Permanently classifies fentanyl-related substances as Schedule I drugs, sets criminal penalties for them, and eases some rules for researchers.	This law changes the Controlled Substances Act by permanently placing an entire class of "fentanyl-related substances" into Schedule I, the strictest category of controlled drugs. It defines these substances based on their chemical similarity to fentanyl, so that new chemical variations are automatically covered. The Attorney General can publish a list of these substances, but a drug is still controlled even if it is not on that list.\n\nThe law also sets criminal penalties for making, importing, exporting, or trafficking these substances, adding them to existing sentencing rules under the Controlled Substances Act and the Controlled Substances Import and Export Act.\n\nAt the same time, the law makes it easier for scientists to study Schedule I drugs. It creates faster registration steps for certain government-funded or drug-development research, lets more than one researcher at an institution work under a single registration, allows related research sites in the same area to share one registration, and permits small-scale manufacturing tied to approved research. Researchers can keep working on a substance newly added to Schedule I while their paperwork is processed.\n\nThose directly affected include people who make, sell, or transport fentanyl-related substances, who face federal charges and penalties, and scientists and research institutions studying these drugs, who follow the new registration procedures. The Attorney General and the Drug Enforcement Administration must issue rules and post information about special research processes.	2026-07-16 05:33:45.642148+00	2026-07-16 05:35:10.78978+00
6	119	s	129	No Tax on Tips Act	passed_senate	Taxation	2025-01-16	https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/senate-bill/129	Held at the desk.	2025-05-26	2025-05-27 08:05:17+00	2026-07-16 05:34:31.61252+00	178913f7e4330a744c3a3c09ac0a4c39fb9852d342ec12471b1642383b20aade	Engrossed in Senate	https://www.congress.gov/119/bills/s129/BILLS-119s129es.htm	complete	claude-opus-4-8	1	1	2026-07-16 05:35:59.579429+00	178913f7e4330a744c3a3c09ac0a4c39fb9852d342ec12471b1642383b20aade	Creates a federal income tax deduction of up to $25,000 for tips and extends an employer tax credit to beauty service businesses.	The bill, called the "No Tax on Tips Act," changes the Internal Revenue Code of 1986 to let workers deduct the cash tips they report to their employer from their taxable income. The deduction is capped at $25,000 per year and is available whether or not a taxpayer itemizes their deductions.\n\nTo count, tips must come from a job in an occupation that traditionally and customarily received tips on or before December 31, 2023. The Treasury Department must publish a list of these occupations within 90 days of the law taking effect. Workers who earned above a set high-income threshold (tied to the definition of a "highly compensated employee") in the prior year from that employer cannot claim the deduction for tips from that employer.\n\nThe bill also expands an existing tax credit that reimburses employers for part of the Social Security taxes they pay on employee tips. Currently available mainly to food and beverage businesses, the credit would also apply to beauty service businesses, including barbering and hair care, nail care, esthetics, and body and spa treatments.\n\nThe changes would apply to tax years beginning after December 31, 2024. Tipped workers, high earners excluded by the income limit, and beauty and food service employers are the groups most directly affected.	2026-07-16 05:33:45.592696+00	2026-07-16 05:35:10.78978+00
7	119	s	146	TAKE IT DOWN Act	enacted	Science, Technology, Communications	2025-01-16	https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/senate-bill/146	Became Public Law No: 119-12.	2025-05-19	2026-06-16 14:19:53+00	2026-07-16 05:34:37.223528+00	2349af5e9eaa2f2a6480b7d7d73acc6ac6ecea0af5342d39737e33152d682201	Public Law	https://www.congress.gov/119/plaws/publ12/PLAW-119publ12.htm	complete	claude-opus-4-8	1	1	2026-07-16 05:36:08.106097+00	2349af5e9eaa2f2a6480b7d7d73acc6ac6ecea0af5342d39737e33152d682201	Makes it a crime to share nonconsensual intimate images, including AI-made fakes, and requires online platforms to remove them within 48 hours.	This law, called the Tools to Address Known Exploitation by Immobilizing Technological Deepfakes on Websites and Networks Act (TAKE IT DOWN Act), makes it a federal crime to knowingly publish intimate images of a person without their consent using the internet. This includes both real photos and "digital forgeries"—fake images created with software or artificial intelligence that look real. The rules cover images of both adults and minors, and also make it illegal to threaten to share such images.\n\nPeople convicted can face fines and prison time. Sentences reach up to 2 years for offenses involving adults and up to 3 years for those involving minors, with additional penalties for threats. Courts can also require offenders to give up related property and pay money to victims. The law lists exceptions, such as disclosures for law enforcement, legal proceedings, medical purposes, or reporting the material.\n\nThe law also requires "covered platforms"—websites and apps that mainly host user-generated content—to set up a process, within one year, that lets a person request removal of intimate images of themselves posted without consent. Once a valid request is received, the platform must remove the image within 48 hours and try to take down identical copies. The Federal Trade Commission (FTC) enforces these removal rules.\n\nThose directly affected include victims of nonconsensual intimate images, people who post such images, and companies that run websites and apps hosting user content.	2026-07-16 05:33:45.61048+00	2026-07-16 05:35:10.78978+00
1	119	hr	2138	Veterans’ Compensation Cost-of-Living Adjustment Act of 2025	committee	Armed Forces and National Security	2025-03-14	https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/house-bill/2138	Subcommittee Hearings Held	2025-03-26	2026-07-15 08:07:34+00	2026-07-16 05:34:22.161787+00	f8f76953ee2c2a13bd77844e7bbdb31534d80c6c9bb5d14c93bee8890c797833	Introduced in House	https://www.congress.gov/119/bills/hr2138/BILLS-119hr2138ih.htm	complete	claude-opus-4-8	1	1	2026-07-16 05:36:25.451979+00	f8f76953ee2c2a13bd77844e7bbdb31534d80c6c9bb5d14c93bee8890c797833	Raises disability compensation for veterans and survivor benefits, effective December 1, 2025, by the same percentage as the Social Security cost-of-living increase.	This bill directs the Secretary of Veterans Affairs to increase the dollar amounts paid for veterans' disability compensation and for dependency and indemnity compensation, which goes to certain survivors of disabled veterans. The increase would take effect on December 1, 2025.\n\nThe size of the increase would match the percentage rise in Social Security benefits under Title II of the Social Security Act for the same period. This is known as a cost-of-living adjustment (COLA), meant to keep benefit values in line with changes in the cost of living. The bill covers wartime disability payments, extra payments for dependents, the clothing allowance, and benefits paid to surviving spouses and children.\n\nThe Secretary must publish the new, adjusted payment amounts in the Federal Register around the same time the related Social Security figures are published for fiscal year 2026. The people directly affected are veterans with service-connected disabilities and the surviving spouses and children who receive these benefits.	2026-07-16 05:33:45.47167+00	2026-07-16 05:35:10.78978+00
10	119	s	5	Laken Riley Act	enacted	Immigration	2025-01-06	https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/senate-bill/5	Became Public Law No: 119-1.	2025-01-29	2026-06-22 13:54:38+00	2026-07-16 05:34:26.790183+00	afd5f9946f41e315f0d196fb04900f3ae7d4d86c304893c92dfa520c11194cd2	Public Law	https://www.congress.gov/119/plaws/publ1/PLAW-119publ1.htm	complete	claude-opus-4-8	1	1	2026-07-16 05:36:37.86049+00	afd5f9946f41e315f0d196fb04900f3ae7d4d86c304893c92dfa520c11194cd2	Requires federal officials to detain immigrants charged with theft-related crimes and lets state officials sue over immigration enforcement decisions.	The Laken Riley Act changes the Immigration and Nationality Act, the main federal law about who can enter and stay in the United States. It requires the Secretary of Homeland Security to take into custody certain immigrants who are in the country unlawfully and who are charged with, arrested for, convicted of, or admit to crimes such as burglary, theft, larceny, shoplifting, or assault of a law enforcement officer, or any crime causing death or serious bodily injury. For these people, the Department of Homeland Security must issue a detainer and take custody if they are not already held by other authorities.\n\nThe law defines the listed crimes using the meaning they have in the state or local area where the acts happened. This means a person can be detained based on being charged, not only on being convicted.\n\nThe Act also gives state attorneys general and other authorized state officers new power to sue the federal government. They can bring lawsuits in federal court asking a judge to order the government to follow immigration detention and removal rules, or to challenge decisions to release immigrants or grant them bond or parole. A state can claim harm if it or its residents face costs, including financial harm of more than $100, and courts are told to speed up these cases.\n\nThe people most directly affected are immigrants who lack legal status and face the listed criminal charges, federal agencies like the Department of Homeland Security and the State Department that must carry out these rules, and state officials who gain the ability to sue over enforcement decisions.	2026-07-16 05:33:45.658469+00	2026-07-16 05:35:10.78978+00
4	119	hr	28	Protection of Women and Girls in Sports Act of 2025	passed_house	Civil Rights and Liberties, Minority Issues	2025-01-03	https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/house-bill/28	Received in the Senate.	2025-01-15	2026-07-11 02:08:18+00	2026-07-16 05:34:11.05678+00	6c1db6dcd08ca3d541b15ee7f06644b0cea78991f030112d89263c5cde04a7d3	Engrossed in House	https://www.congress.gov/119/bills/hr28/BILLS-119hr28eh.htm	complete	claude-opus-4-8	1	1	2026-07-16 05:36:45.383926+00	6c1db6dcd08ca3d541b15ee7f06644b0cea78991f030112d89263c5cde04a7d3	Requires schools getting federal money to base sex on birth biology for Title IX sports, barring males from women's and girls' teams.	This bill changes Title IX of the Education Amendments of 1972, a law that bans sex discrimination in education programs that receive federal money. It adds a rule about how sex is defined when it comes to school sports.\n\nUnder the bill, schools, colleges, and other groups that get federal financial assistance cannot let a person whose sex is male take part in an athletic program or activity that is set aside for women or girls. Sex would be determined only by a person's reproductive biology and genetics at birth. The bill still allows males to practice or train with women's or girls' teams, as long as no female loses a roster spot, a chance to play, a scholarship, school admission, or any other benefit that comes with participation.\n\nThe bill also directs the Comptroller General, who leads the Government Accountability Office (GAO), to study what "any other benefit" means. The study would look at the effects on girls of allowing males to compete in girls' sports, and the results would be reported to committees in the House of Representatives and the Senate.\n\nThe people most directly affected are students who play school and college sports, transgender girls and women who were male at birth, and the schools and athletic programs that receive federal funding and must follow these rules.	2026-07-16 05:33:45.554711+00	2026-07-16 05:35:10.78978+00
3	119	hr	25	FairTax Act of 2025	committee	Taxation	2025-01-03	https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/house-bill/25	Referred to the House Committee on Ways and Means.	2025-01-03	2025-09-11 13:32:33+00	2026-07-16 05:34:06.418892+00	0dff22e3a81b144a56d39772518f622c12e5378125ce100cf5d92aa4b8be2b46	Introduced in House	https://www.congress.gov/119/bills/hr25/BILLS-119hr25ih.htm	complete	claude-opus-4-8	1	1	2026-07-16 05:36:56.361911+00	0dff22e3a81b144a56d39772518f622c12e5378125ce100cf5d92aa4b8be2b46	Repeals federal income, payroll, and estate taxes, abolishes the IRS, and replaces them with a 23% national sales tax collected mostly by states.	The FairTax Act of 2025 would eliminate the federal income tax, payroll taxes (which fund Social Security and Medicare), and estate and gift taxes. It would also shut down the Internal Revenue Service (IRS). In their place, the bill creates a national sales tax on most goods and services that people buy for final use or consumption.\n\nStarting in 2027, the tax would be 23% of the total price paid (this is figured as part of the total price, not added on top). Businesses would collect the tax when they sell to customers, and states with their own sales taxes would handle most of the collection and pass the money to the U.S. Treasury in exchange for a small fee. Purchases made for business, investment, or export would not be taxed, and used items would generally not be taxed again. To offset taxes on basic needs, every registered household would receive a monthly rebate (called a family consumption allowance) based on federal poverty guidelines and family size.\n\nSocial Security and Medicare would still be funded, but from the new sales tax revenue and general government funds instead of payroll taxes. Employers would still report wages to the Social Security Administration so benefits can be calculated. The bill sets rules for how the tax applies to things like insurance, financial services, government purchases, and nonprofit organizations.\n\nThe changes would directly affect nearly all consumers, businesses that sell goods and services, state tax agencies, and IRS employees. The bill also includes a sunset provision: if the 16th Amendment to the Constitution (which allows the federal income tax) is not repealed within seven years, the national sales tax would end.	2026-07-16 05:33:45.530202+00	2026-07-16 05:35:10.78978+00
